Parson will sell everything that isn&rsquo;t nailed down.
 When the media, crooked businessmen, and corrupt politicians were in the midst of their coup against Eric Greitens, a friend told me, &ldquo;If they get rid of Greitens, Parson will sell everything that isn&rsquo;t nailed down.&rdquo;
My friend was wrong. Governor Mike Parson (who may or may not have been a conspirator in the coup) is selling everything in Missouri, but he isn&rsquo;t stopping at the loose items.

Governor Eric Greitens resigned. Friend of the lobbyists, Mike Parson, became Missouri&rsquo;s governor. In the words of someone who knows the new governor well, Mike Parson will &ldquo;sell everything that isn&rsquo;t nailed down.&rdquo;
For those of us who believe in limited government that doesn&rsquo;t put its thumb on the scale of achievement, it&rsquo;s time to panic and despair, right?
Wrong. It&rsquo;s never time to panic or despair. And we know this from two of the greatest philosophers of all time, Epictetus and Seneca.

&ldquo;What if everything goes wrong?&rdquo;
I remember asking myself that on the morning of Friday, February 27, 2009.
I was driving on I-44 headed to the Arch to host a Tea Party. My co-hosts were people I&rsquo;d never met: Dana Loesch, Gina Loudon, Ed Martin, Michelle Moore. Those were the three to offered to help. Others offered to speak: Jim Lembke, Shamed Dogan, and a few others. Others helped organize sign-making, food, sign-in sheets, and music.
